#. Tag: para
#: adm_sudo.xml:19
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"Many commands and system utilities need to be run as &rootuser; to modify "
"files and/or perform tasks that only the super user is allowed to. For "
"security reasons and to avoid accidentally running dangerous commands, it is "
"generally advisable not to log in directly as &rootuser;. Instead, it is "
"recommended to work as a normal, unprivileged user and use the &sudo; "
"command to run commands with elevated privileges."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: adm_sudo.xml:27
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"On &productname;, &sudo; is configured by default to work similarly to su. "
"However, &sudo; offers the possibility to allow users to run commands with "
"privileges of any other user in a highly configurable manner. This can be "
"used to assign roles with specific privileges to certain users and groups. "
"It is for example possible to allow members of the group &examplegroup; to "
"run a command with the privileges of &exampleuserII;. Access to the command "
"can be further restricted by, for example, forbidding to specify any command "
"options. While su always requires the &rootuser; password for authentication "
"with PAM, &sudo; can be configured to authenticate with your own "
"credentials. This increases security by not having to share the &rootuser; "
"password. For instance, you can allow members of the group &examplegroup; to "
"run a command <command>frobnicate</command> as &exampleuserII;, with the "
"restriction that no arguments are specified. This can be used to assign "
"roles with specific abilities to certain users and groups."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: adm_sudo.xml:44
#, no-c-format
msgid "Basic &sudo; Usage"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: adm_sudo.xml:46
#, no-c-format
msgid "&sudo; is simple to use, yet very powerful."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: adm_sudo.xml:51
#, no-c-format
msgid "Running a Single Command"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: adm_sudo.xml:52
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"Logged in as normal user, you can run any command as &rootuser; by adding "
"&sudo; before it. It will prompt for the root password and, if authenticated "
"successfully, run the command as &rootuser;:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: adm_sudo.xml:57
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"&prompt.user;<command>id -un</command><co xml:id=\"co.sudo.usage.id\"/>\n"
"tux\n"
"&prompt.user;<command>sudo id -un</command>\n"
"root's password:<co xml:id=\"co.sudo.usage.pw\"/>\n"
"root\n"
"&prompt.user;<command>id -un</command>\n"
"tux<co xml:id=\"co.sudo.usage.after\"/>\n"
"&prompt.user;<command>sudo id -un</command>\n"
"<co xml:id=\"co.sudo.usage.nopw\"/>\n"
"root"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: adm_sudo.xml:60
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"The <command>id -un</command> command prints the login name of the current "
"user."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: adm_sudo.xml:66
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"The password is not shown during input, neither as clear text nor as bullets."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: adm_sudo.xml:72
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"Only commands started with &sudo; are run with elevated privileges. If you "
"run the same command without the &sudo; prefix, it is run with the "
"privileges of the current user again."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: adm_sudo.xml:79
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"For a limited amount of time, you do not need to enter the &rootuser; "
"password again."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: adm_sudo.xml:86
#, no-c-format
msgid "I/O Redirection"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: adm_sudo.xml:87
#, no-c-format
msgid "I/O redirection does not work as you would probably expect:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: adm_sudo.xml:90
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"&prompt.user; sudo echo s &gt; /proc/sysrq-trigger\n"
"bash: /proc/sysrq-trigger: Permission denied\n"
"&prompt.user; sudo cat &lt; /proc/1/maps\n"
"bash: /proc/1/maps: Permission denied"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: adm_sudo.xml:91
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"Only the <command>echo</command>/<command>cat</command> binary is run with "
"elevated privileges, while the redirection is performed by the user's shell "
"with user privileges. You can either start a shell like in <xref linkend="
"\"sec.sudo.shell\"/> or use the <command>dd</command> utility instead:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: adm_sudo.xml:98
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"echo s | sudo dd of=/proc/sysrq-trigger\n"
"sudo dd if=/proc/1/maps | cat <!-- TODO: Better example! -->"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: adm_sudo.xml:103
#, no-c-format
msgid "Starting a Shell"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: adm_sudo.xml:104
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"Having to add &sudo; before every command can be cumbersome. While you could "
"specify a shell as a command <command>sudo bash</command>, it is recommended "
"to rather use one of the built-in mechanisms to start a shell:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: literal
#: adm_sudo.xml:111
#, no-c-format
msgid "sudo -s (&lt;command&gt;)"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: adm_sudo.xml:114
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"Starts a shell specified by the <envar>SHELL</envar> environment variable or "
"the target user's default shell. If a command is given, it is passed to the "
"shell (with the <option>-c</option> option), else the shell is run in "
"interactive mode."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: adm_sudo.xml:120
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"<prompt>&exampleuser_plain;:~ &gt; </prompt>sudo -i\n"
"root's password:\n"
"<prompt>root:/home/tux # </prompt>exit\n"
"<prompt>&exampleuser_plain;:~ &gt; </prompt>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: literal
#: adm_sudo.xml:124
#, no-c-format
msgid "sudo -i (&lt;command&gt;)"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: adm_sudo.xml:127
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"Like <option>-s</option>, but starts the shell as login shell. This means "
"that the shell's start-up files (<filename>.profile</filename> etc.) are "
"processed and the current working directory is set to the target user's home "
"directory."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: adm_sudo.xml:133
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"<prompt>&exampleuser_plain;:~ &gt; </prompt>sudo -i\n"
"root's password:\n"
"<prompt>root:~ # </prompt>exit\n"
"<prompt>&exampleuser_plain;:~ &gt; </prompt>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: adm_sudo.xml:140
#, no-c-format
msgid "Environment Variables"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: adm_sudo.xml:141
#, no-c-format
msgid "By default, &sudo; does not propagate environment variables:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: adm_sudo.xml:144
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"&prompt.user;ENVVAR=test env | grep ENVVAR\n"
"ENVVAR=test\n"
"&prompt.user;ENVVAR=test sudo env | grep ENVVAR\n"
"root's password:\n"
"<co xml:id=\"co.sudo.env.novar\"/>\n"
"&prompt.user;"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: adm_sudo.xml:147
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"The empty output shows that the environment variable <envar>ENVVAR</envar> "
"did not exist in the context of the command run with &sudo;."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: adm_sudo.xml:154
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"This behavior can be changed by the <literal>env_reset</literal> option, see "
"<xref linkend=\"tab.adm.sudo.options\"/>."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: adm_sudo.xml:161
#, no-c-format
msgid "Configuring &sudo;"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: adm_sudo.xml:163
#, no-c-format
msgid "&sudo; is a very flexible tool with extensive configuration."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: adm_sudo.xml:168
#, no-c-format
msgid "Locked yourself out of sudo"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: adm_sudo.xml:169
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"If you locked yourself out of &sudo; by mistake, you can use <command>su -</"
"command> and the &rootuser; password to get a root shell and run "
"<command>visudo</command> to fix the error."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: adm_sudo.xml:177
#, no-c-format
msgid "Editing the Configuration Files"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: adm_sudo.xml:181
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"The main policy configuration file for &sudo; is <filename>/etc/sudoers</"
"filename>. As it is possible to lock yourself out of the system if there are "
"any errors in that file, it is strongly recommended to use <command>visudo</"
"command> for editing. It will prevent simultaneous changes to the opened "
"file and check for syntax errors before saving."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: adm_sudo.xml:189
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"Despite its name, you can also use editors other than vi by setting the "
"<envar>EDITOR</envar> environment variable, for example:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: adm_sudo.xml:193
#, no-c-format
msgid "sudo EDITOR=<replaceable>/usr/bin/nano</replaceable> visudo"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: adm_sudo.xml:194
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"However, the <filename>/etc/sudoers</filename> file itself is supplied by "
"the system packages and modifications may break on updates. Therefore, it is "
"recommended to put custom configuration into files in the <filename>/etc/"
"sudoers.d/</filename> directory. Any file in there is automatically "
"included. To create or edit a file in that subdirectory, run:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: adm_sudo.xml:201
#, no-c-format
msgid "sudo visudo -f /etc/sudoers.d/<replaceable>NAME</replaceable>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: adm_sudo.xml:202
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"Alternatively with a different editor (for example <command>nano</command>):"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: adm_sudo.xml:206
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"sudo EDITOR=<replaceable>/usr/bin/nano</replaceable> visudo -f /etc/sudoers."
"d/<replaceable>NAME</replaceable>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: adm_sudo.xml:208
#, no-c-format
msgid "Ignored Files in <filename>/etc/sudoers.d</filename>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: adm_sudo.xml:209
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"The <literal>#includedir</literal> command in <filename>/etc/sudoers</"
"filename>, used for <filename>/etc/sudoers.d</filename>, ignores files that "
"end in <literal>~</literal> (tilde) or contain a <literal>.</literal> (dot)."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: adm_sudo.xml:216
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"For more information on the <command>visudo</command> command, run "
"<command>man 8 visudo</command>."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: adm_sudo.xml:223
#, no-c-format
msgid "Basic sudoers Configuration Syntax"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: adm_sudo.xml:224
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"In the sudoers configuration files, there are two types of options: strings "
"and flags. While strings can contain any value, flags can be turned either "
"ON or OFF. The most important syntax constructs for sudoers configuration "
"files are:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: adm_sudo.xml:230
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"# Everything on a line after a # gets ignored <co xml:id=\"co.sudo.syntax."
"comment\"/>\n"
"Defaults !insults # Disable the insults flag <co xml:id=\"co.sudo.syntax.flag"
"\"/>\n"
"Defaults env_keep += \"DISPLAY HOME\" # Add DISPLAY and HOME to env_keep\n"
"&exampleuser_plain; ALL = NOPASSWD: /usr/bin/frobnicate, PASSWD: /usr/bin/"
"journalctl <co xml:id=\"co.sudo.syntax.rule\"/>"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: adm_sudo.xml:233
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"There are two exceptions: <literal>#include</literal> and "
"<literal>#includedir</literal> are normal commands. Followed by digits, it "
"specifies a UID."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: adm_sudo.xml:240
#, no-c-format
msgid "Remove the <literal>!</literal> to set the specified flag to ON."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: adm_sudo.xml:245
#, no-c-format
msgid "See <xref linkend=\"sec.sudo.conf.rule\"/>."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: adm_sudo.xml:251
#, no-c-format
msgid "Useful Flags and Options"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: adm_sudo.xml:256
#, no-c-format
msgid "Option name"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: adm_sudo.xml:261
#, no-c-format
msgid "Description"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: adm_sudo.xml:266
#, no-c-format
msgid "Example"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: literal
#: adm_sudo.xml:274
#, no-c-format
msgid "targetpw"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: adm_sudo.xml:277
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"This flag controls whether the invoking user is required to enter the "
"password of the target user (ON) (for example &rootuser;) or the invoking "
"user (OFF)."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: adm_sudo.xml:284
#, no-c-format
msgid "Defaults targetpw # Turn targetpw flag ON"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: literal
#: adm_sudo.xml:288
#, no-c-format
msgid "rootpw"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: adm_sudo.xml:291
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"If set, &sudo; will prompt for the &rootuser; password instead of the target "
"user's or the invoker's. The default is OFF."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: adm_sudo.xml:297
#, no-c-format
msgid "Defaults !rootpw # Turn rootpw flag OFF"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: literal
#: adm_sudo.xml:301
#, no-c-format
msgid "env_reset"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: adm_sudo.xml:304
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"If set, &sudo; constructs a minimal environment with only <envar>TERM</"
"envar>, <envar>PATH</envar>, <envar>HOME</envar>, <envar>MAIL</envar>, "
"<envar>SHELL</envar>, <envar>LOGNAME</envar>, <envar>USER</envar>, "
"<envar>USERNAME</envar>, and <envar>SUDO_*</envar> set. Additionally, "
"variables listed in <literal>env_keep</literal> get imported from the "
"calling environment. The default is ON."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: adm_sudo.xml:315
#, no-c-format
msgid "Defaults env_reset # Turn env_reset flag ON"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: literal
#: adm_sudo.xml:319
#, no-c-format
msgid "env_keep"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: adm_sudo.xml:322
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"List of environment variables to keep when the <literal>env_reset</literal> "
"flag is ON."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: adm_sudo.xml:328
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"# Set env_keep to contain EDITOR and PROMPT\n"
"Defaults env_keep = \"EDITOR PROMPT\"\n"
"Defaults env_keep += \"JRE_HOME\" # Add JRE_HOME\n"
"Defaults env_keep -= \"JRE_HOME\" # Remove JRE_HOME"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: literal
#: adm_sudo.xml:332
#, no-c-format
msgid "env_delete"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: adm_sudo.xml:335
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"List of environment variables to remove when the <literal>env_reset</"
"literal> flag is OFF."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: adm_sudo.xml:341
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"# Set env_delete to contain EDITOR and PROMPT\n"
"Defaults env_delete = \"EDITOR PROMPT\"\n"
"Defaults env_delete += \"JRE_HOME\" # Add JRE_HOME\n"
"Defaults env_delete -= \"JRE_HOME\" # Remove JRE_HOME"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: adm_sudo.xml:347
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"The <literal>Defaults</literal> token can also be used to create aliases for "
"a collection of users, hosts, and commands. Furthermore, it is possible to "
"apply an option only to a specific set of users."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: adm_sudo.xml:352
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"For detailed information about the <filename>/etc/sudoers</filename> "
"configuration file, consult <command>man 5 sudoers</command>."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: adm_sudo.xml:359
#, no-c-format
msgid "Rules in sudoers"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: adm_sudo.xml:360
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"Rules in the sudoers configuration can be very complex, so this section will "
"only cover the basics. Each rule follows the basic scheme (<literal>[]</"
"literal> marks optional parts):"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: adm_sudo.xml:365
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"#Who      Where         As whom      Tag                What\n"
"User_List Host_List = [(User_List)] [NOPASSWD:|PASSWD:] Cmnd_List"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: title
#: adm_sudo.xml:367
#, no-c-format
msgid "Syntax for sudoers Rules"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: literal
#: adm_sudo.xml:369
#, no-c-format
msgid "User_List"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: adm_sudo.xml:372
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"One or more (separated by <literal>,</literal>) identifiers: Either a user "
"name, a group in the format <literal>%GROUPNAME</literal> or a user ID in "
"the format <literal>#UID</literal>. Negation can be performed with a "
"<literal>!</literal> prefix."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: literal
#: adm_sudo.xml:381
#, no-c-format
msgid "Host_List"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: adm_sudo.xml:384
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"One or more (separated by <literal>,</literal>) identifiers: Either a (fully "
"qualified) host name or an IP address. Negation can be performed with a "
"<literal>!</literal> prefix. <literal>ALL</literal> is the usual choice for "
"<literal>Host_List</literal>."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: literal
#: adm_sudo.xml:393
#, no-c-format
msgid "NOPASSWD:|PASSWD:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: adm_sudo.xml:396
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"The user will not be prompted for a password when running commands matching "
"<literal>CMDSPEC</literal> after <literal>NOPASSWD:</literal>."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: adm_sudo.xml:400
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"<literal>PASSWD</literal> is the default, it only needs to be specified when "
"both are on the same line:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: adm_sudo.xml:404
#, no-c-format
msgid "&exampleuser_plain; ALL = PASSWD: /usr/bin/foo, NOPASSWD: /usr/bin/bar"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: literal
#: adm_sudo.xml:408
#, no-c-format
msgid "Cmnd_List"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: adm_sudo.xml:411
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"One or more (separated by <literal>,</literal>) specifiers: A path to an "
"executable, followed by allowed arguments or nothing."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: adm_sudo.xml:415
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"/usr/bin/foo     # Anything allowed\n"
"/usr/bin/foo bar # Only \"/usr/bin/foo bar\" allowed\n"
"/usr/bin/foo \"\"  # No arguments allowed"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: adm_sudo.xml:419
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"<literal>ALL</literal> can be used as <literal>User_List</literal>, "
"<literal>Host_List</literal>, and <literal>Cmnd_List</literal>."
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: adm_sudo.xml:423
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"A rule that allows &exampleuser; to run all commands as root without "
"entering a password:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: adm_sudo.xml:427
#, no-c-format
msgid "&exampleuser_plain; ALL = NOPASSWD: ALL"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: adm_sudo.xml:428
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"A rule that allows &exampleuser; to run <command>systemctl restart apache2</"
"command>:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: adm_sudo.xml:432
#, no-c-format
msgid "&exampleuser_plain; ALL = /usr/bin/systemctl restart apache2"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: para
#: adm_sudo.xml:433
#, no-c-format
msgid ""
"A rule that allows &exampleuser; to run <command>wall</command> as "
"<systemitem>admin</systemitem> with no arguments:"
msgstr ""

#. Tag: screen
#: adm_sudo.xml:437
#, no-c-format
msgid "&exampleuser_plain; ALL = (admin) /usr/bin/wall \"\""
msgstr ""

